On my first visit to Tokyo in 2004, when I stood bewildered by the video screens of Shibuya, I wondered to what extent this advertising technology would be ramped up in 10 years’ time. How much more extreme could it—would it—get? The answer is none. The Shibuya scramble looks exactly the same today as it did almost a decade ago. The future in Japan has come and gone. It’s now in Seoul, whose vertical city planning feels so much more futuristic than the 20th century sprawl of Tokyo, and the new mega-cities of China, which reflect the massive urbanization of our species.
